ce:section.ce:para:
The photocatalytic ability of N–Bi-CDs/TNP composite in degrading DCF of different initial concentration was performed in the range of 5–25 ppm under natural sunlight irradiation. Fig. 8
                        a reveals the photocatalytic performance of N–Bi-CDs/TNP in removing DCF of different initial concentrations. At high initial DCF concentration, the removal efficiency of DCF drops from 100% to 70% after 360 min of sunlight irradiation. The photodegradation efficiency depends on the generation of hydroxyl radicals. At higher initial concentration of DCF molecules, the ratio of photocatalyst to DCF reduces. There are more DCF molecules to be removed at a constant amount of photocatalyst. Hence, less radical species are generated due to limited active sites available in photocatalyst, thus leading to lower photocatalytic removal efficiency (Lara-Pérez et al., 2020). The degradation profiles are fitted into Langmuir-Hinshelwood pseudo-first order kinetics model as shown in Fig. 8b, which represented by equation -ln (C/C0) = kt. C and C0 are concentration at time t and initial concentration of DCF at time 0, respectively, while k is the removal rate constant. The degradation profile shows perfect fitting in the pseudo-first order kinetics model with R2 values of 0.9520, 0.9609 and 0.9698, respectively. The rate of mineralization represents the rate of conversion of DCF into mineralized products such as CO2, H2O and other organic compounds (Kovacic et al., 2016). Rate of mineralization of DCF is evaluating by measuring the total organic carbon (TOC) of the DCF solution after being treated using N–Bi-CDs/TNP composite for 5–25 ppm initial concentrations (Table 2
                        ). At 5 ppm, the TOC removal efficiency is measured to be 87.63%. When initial concentrations of DCF increased to 10 ppm and 25 ppm, the TOC removal efficiencies dropped to 63.00% and 58.84%, respectively.
